<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[Syria accused of ‘pervasive’ torture in first global case over civil war]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/10/syria-accused-of-pervasive-torture-in-first-global-case-over-civil-war]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T10:54:44Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fc7fb8e12f9dfc84da4b76dfe073c6f3ef528bc7/0_288_8640_5184 /master/8640.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=48c2ec3a0795885ebd1fa0c8f4dbec4c&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;海牙国际法院外的人们展示了他们所说的在叙利亚“失踪”的人的照片.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;世界法院法官审理了第一起与该国内战有关的国际案件，叙利亚折磨了数万名人民，并维持着“广泛而普遍”的“令人憎恶的待遇”制度.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;加拿大和荷兰之前已将&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/syria&quot;>;叙利亚&lt;/a>;带入&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/law/international-court-of-justice&quot;>;国际法院&lt;/a>; (ICJ)，寻求采取紧急措施，制止对数千名仍被拘留的人的虐待。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“每一天都很重要，”荷兰最高代表勒内​​·勒费伯 (René Lefeber) 告诉法庭。 “目前在叙利亚被拘留或有被拘留风险的人不能再等了。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;大马士革冷落了第一天的听证会，并此前将该案斥为“虚假信息和谎言”，并表示这些指控“缺乏丝毫可信度”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Lefeber 引用了被拘留者的痛苦证词，描述了轮奸、残害和“标准化”惩罚方法，包括将人扭曲成汽车轮胎并进行“严厉殴打” ”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;加拿大和荷兰已要求国际法院“紧急”要求叙利亚停止一切酷刑和任意拘留，向外部检查人员开放监狱，并向家人提供有关亲人命运的信息。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;国际法院可能需要数年时间才能对案件做出裁决，但紧急“临时措施”可以在几周内下令，并且具有法律约束力。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我们真诚地相信，叙利亚人的生命和福祉受到威胁，需要法院立即予以关注。”Lefeber 说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;前囚犯、现为活动人士的艾哈迈德·赫尔米 (Ahmad Helmi) 表示：“我在叙利亚的监狱里呆了三年多年来，我确信酷刑正在昼夜不停地发生。这种情况每时每刻都会发生。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这种情况不仅仅发生在审讯过程中。有时它是为了好玩而发生的。仅仅因为他们觉得自己享受有罪不罚的感觉，他们就可以为所欲为。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“每个月都有数百人在酷刑下死亡，”赫尔米在听证会前接受采访时说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; >;人权观察组织的 Balkees Jarrah 表示，国际法院需要采取行动“防止叙利亚人遭受进一步的虐待，他们继续在噩梦般的条件下受苦，生命处于严重危险之中”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一些国家出现了与叙利亚战争有关的个别战争罪案件，西方国家长期以来一直对缺乏更广泛的国际正义计划感到沮丧。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;荷兰人于 2020 年 9 月首次发起了一场运动，要求叙利亚涉嫌违反《联合国禁止酷刑公约》，大马士革是该公约的签署国。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;加拿大于 2021 年 3 月加入此案。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu ://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/law/international-criminal-court&quot;>;国际刑事法院&lt;/a>; (ICC) – 一个战争罪法庭，与国际法院一样，设在海牙——自从大马士革从未批准该法庭的成立条约《罗马规约》以来，海牙一直无法处理叙利亚问题。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;俄罗斯和中国阻止了联合国安理会将叙利亚局势提交国际刑事法院的决议草案。 2014 年。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;叙利亚总统巴沙尔·阿萨德 (Bashar al-Assad) 5 月份重返国际舞台并出席阿拉伯联盟峰会后，局势再次受到关注。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;将听证会描述为这是一个“分水岭”案件，人权观察组织表示，希望国际法院的诉讼程序能够让人们关注阿萨德从孤立中恢复的情况。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;赫尔米表示，尽管“流氓国家”叙利亚没有机会接受叙利亚的任何决定，国际法院的判决对于受害者和家庭来说仍然很重要。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我们不是在谈论某个地方的地方法院。这不是我说酷刑正在发生。这将是国际法院说酷刑正在发生，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“无论谁想要使叙利亚政权重新正常化，他们的额头上都会贴上这个标签，表明你正在以一个国家实现正常化。日以继夜地折磨着人们。”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 19:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[UK and Ireland confirmed as hosts for men’s Euro 2028 by Uefa]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/10/uk-and-ireland-confirmed-hosts-euro-2028-men-uefa]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T10:10:50Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/612af51d1a9976d1a87e6ecd3386dbf4c4a60215/96_56_3260_1956 /master/3260.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=2ae40bc10695cbd539ca82e8321d7a16&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;英格兰、爱尔兰共和国、北爱尔兰、苏格兰和威尔士的队长&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;英国欧足联已确认爱尔兰和爱尔兰为男子&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/football/european-championship&quot;>;欧洲锦标赛&lt;/a的东道主>; 2028 年。该决定是在 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/04/uk-and-ireland-set-to-host-euro-2028-after -turkey-withdraw-bid&quot;>;土耳其上周撤回了申办&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;欧足联向欧足联提议在五个主办国的 10 个场地举办锦标赛，共有 24 支球队参赛，其中 10 支球队。 6这些场馆位于英格兰，北爱尔兰、爱尔兰共和国、苏格兰和威尔士各有一个。这提高了温布利举办 2028 年决赛的可能性，七年后，温布利举办了&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jul/11/italy-crush-england-dreams-after-wining -euro-2020-on-penalties&quot;>;男子欧洲杯决赛&lt;/a>;以及举办六年后&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jul/31/england-germany -womens-euro-2022-final-match-report&quot;>;女子欧洲杯决赛&lt;/a>;。大约将出售三百万张门票，组织者的目标是公平定价。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周二，集体申办向欧足联执行委员会进行了汇报，随后比赛的奖项就被盖上了橡皮图章。申办领导者估计，2028 年世界杯预计将为五个主办国带来约 30 亿欧元（26 亿英镑）的经济效益。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-interactive=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk /embed/iframe-wrapper/0.1/boot.js&quot; data-canonical-url=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2023/04/euro-2028bidstadiums/giv-13425wrJBBfUSKP9f/&quot; 数据-alt=&quot;2028 年欧洲杯体育场馆&quot;>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2023/04/euro-2028bidstadiums/giv-13425wrJBBfUSKP9f/&quot;>;互动&lt;/a>; &lt; /figure>; &lt;p>;五支球队预计将以正常方式参加资格赛，欧足联为未能晋级的东道主球队保留两个“安全网”席位。如果超过两支球队未能晋级，则只有战绩最好的两支球队才能获得参赛资格，因此主办国可能会错失良机。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;土耳其和意大利将联合主办 2032 年欧洲杯。&lt;/p>; >; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;更多详细信息很快...&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style =&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank &quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 18:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Country Garden warns it could default on debt]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/oct/10/china-country-garden-default-on-debt-property-developer]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T09:02:57Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/e0718ed2d912792d53444ba2737aed81f50ab04f/0_13_5000_3000 /master/5000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=8c1370445cfd089a8238627f718ddfbb&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;位于中国佛山的碧桂园控股总部&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;中国最大的私人开发商已发出警告可能会拖欠其国际债务，从而对该国陷入困境的房地产行业造成又一次打击。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;碧桂园大约&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/29 /evergrande-shares-china-economy-fears&quot;>;2000 亿美元（1630 亿英镑）的负债&lt;/a>;以及近 110 亿美元的以美元计价的离岸债券。到目前为止，它还没有违约，但自上个月以来，它错过了一些美元债券的息票支付，并面临从下周开始的 30 天付款宽限期的结束。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;它在 &lt;a href 中表示=&quot;https://www.bgy.com.cn/upload/file/2023-10-10/c89af3c5-5ac0-4d88-81ef-f70583b3e250.pdf&quot;>;公司向香港联交所提交的声明&lt;/a>;表示“预计将无法在到期时或相关宽限期内履行所有离岸付款义务，包括但不限于公司发行的美元票据项下的义务”。&lt;/p>; &lt;旁白>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/02/beijings-mixed-messages-leave-businesses-questioning-investments -in-china&quot;>;北京方面含混不清的信息让企业对在中国的投资产生‘质疑’&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;它补充说：“这种不付款可能会导致集团相关债权人要求加速支付所欠的相关债务或采取强制措施。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;碧桂园下周面临重大考验，如果未能支付 9 月份 1500 万美元的息票，其全部离岸债务可能被视为违约。到 10 月 17 日，即 30 天宽限期结束时。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该公司在周二的声明中表示，其销售和融资面临“重大挑战”，销售“承受着巨大压力”，其可用资金继续减少。该公司表示，将“尽最大努力确保物业交付，这是集团最重要的企业责任，也是维护房地产市场的关键支柱”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;股价下跌逾10% %，今年下降了约 70%。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;自从全球负债最重的开发商恒大集团在 2021 年拖欠部分债务以来，房地产行业一直处于危机之中。这场危机拖累了中国经济的四分之一，拖累了整体经济增长。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这是由监管打压引发的，中国政府担心房地产行业的高债务水平，这意味着恒大发现自己无法&lt; a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/sep/09/china-property-market-evergrande-300bn-debt-share-slump&quot;>;偿还超过3000亿美元的利息&lt;/ a>; 2021 年底负债累累，导致中国的住房开发行业陷入流动性危机。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;上周，&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/ 的首席经济学家 Alicia García-Herrero法国投资银行 Natixis 表示，mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/asia-pacific&quot;>;亚太地区&lt;/a>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023 /oct/05/evergrande-the-runaway-developer-that-c​​ould-become-a-wrecking-ball-for-chinas-economy&quot;>;“碧桂园和恒大一样都是大问题”&lt;/a>;中国房地产和商业部门的健康状况。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;自2021年流动性危机袭击该行业以来，占中国房屋销售量40%的公司出现债务违约，导致许多房产未完工。&lt;/p>; &lt; p>;北京近几个月推出了一系列措施，包括降低存款要求和降低现有抵押贷款利率，以帮助重振购房者的信心。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;碧桂园表示已任命投资银行Houlihan Lokey，与部分国有的中国国际金融公司和盛德律师事务所一起作为顾问，检查其资本结构和流动性状况，并提出“整体解决方案”。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 17:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Revealed: Amazon linked to trafficking of workers in Saudi Arabia]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/oct/10/amazon-trafficking-links-claims-saudi-arabia-workers-abuses]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T09:00:36Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/74c1bdd1841c3ad0ac6649231f8ed6ac84b8d17a/0_0_3835_2392 /master/3835.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=84be37bc4923efdd7c165646c3dbc7aa&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;一个在装配线上工作的男人的插图，他思考着农场里与羊（一个女人）在一起的生活和一个男孩&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;蒙塔吉·曼苏尔 (Momtaj Mansur) 想回到他的妈妈和兄弟身边，回到尼泊尔南部平原的牧场。他说，他感觉自己像一名囚犯，关在沙特阿拉伯一间蟑螂出没的工棚里，失业、饥饿、负债累累。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/oct/10/trafficking-inc- Five-takeaways-amazon-mcdonalds-middle-east&quot;>;麦当劳和亚马逊与涉嫌贩卖劳工的关系：五个关键要点&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;这位 23 岁的年轻人于 2021 年来到沙特首都利雅得，为全球最大的公司之一：亚马逊工作。&lt;/p>; &lt;p >;他说，他没有找到梦想的工作，而是发现了低薪和痛苦。他说，亚马逊经理斥责他速度太慢，因为他匆匆穿过一个巨大的两层仓库，抢走了阿拉伯半岛各地顾客订购的 iPhone 和其他商品。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;然后在 2022 年 5 月，他说，他和他的许多尼泊尔同事突然被亚马逊仓库解雇了。他们距离家乡 2,400 英里，没有工资，食物也很少。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;曼苏尔表示，他向沙特劳动力供应公司恳求，该公司持有他们的雇佣合同，并将他们安排在亚马逊担任临时职位：如果有的话没有更多的工作，让他们返回尼泊尔。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他说，沙特公司要求他做出可怕的选择。他可以呆在一个对他来说“就像地狱”的地方。或者，他可以通过支付 1,300 美元的退出费，让他在尼泊尔的家人陷入更深的贫困，这是在合同完成之前离开的罚款。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p>;要么杀了我们，要么送我们回家，但不要给我们带来那么多痛苦&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;Momtaj Mansur&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“我告诉他们：要么杀了我们，要么派出我们“我们回家吧，但不要给我们带来那么多痛苦。”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;蒙塔吉·曼苏尔 (Momtaj Mansur) 是数十名现任和前任工人之一，他们声称自己受到尼泊尔招聘机构和劳动力供应的欺骗和剥削。沙特阿拉伯的公司，然后在亚马逊仓库的恶劣条件下遭受苦难。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他们的账户让我们深入了解美国大公司如何直接或间接地从可能构成劳动力贩运的雇佣行为中获利，这种行为被定义为使用武力、胁迫或欺诈来诱使某人工作或提供服务。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business /2023/oct/10/mcdonalds-trafficking-links-claims-chuck-e-cheese-saudi-arabia&quot;>;麦当劳和 Chuck E Cheese 涉嫌剥削外国工人&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;在接受本报道采访的 54 名尼泊尔工人中，有 48 名表示招聘人员在雇佣条款上误导了他们，错误地承诺他们将直接为亚马逊工作。所有 54 人都表示，他们被要求支付大约 830 美元到 2,300 美元之间的招募费，这远远超出了尼泊尔政府允许的数额，并且违反了美国和联合国的标准。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在沙特阿拉伯期间，这些工人表示，他们的工资只是亚马逊沙特仓库直接雇用的工资的一小部分，因为劳动力供应公司大幅削减了亚马逊为其劳动力支付的工资。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一些工人表示，在他们“当他们在亚马逊被解雇后，他们的劳动力供应公司试图利用沙特法律赋予雇主广泛的权力来控制外国工人的行动自由，从而从他们身上榨取更多的钱。曼苏尔是接受本报道采访的 20 名尼泊尔人之一，他们表示，劳动力供应公司告诉工人，除非他们支付通常相当于几个月工资的出境费，否则他们不能返回尼泊尔。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p >;我们已经付了钱来这里，还需要另外付钱才能回来吗？我们感到被困住了&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;沙特阿拉伯的亚马逊工人&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“我们已经付了钱来到这里，我们必须还要付额外的钱才能回来吗？”一位现任工人说。 “我们感觉被困住了。”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;c9fe59b0f1201bd430aa51b1126ffe7c2a2ab1b1&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/c9fe59b0f1201bd430aa51b1126ffe7c2a2ab1b1/0_0_3073_38 33/802.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;一名年轻人的插图&quot; width=&quot;802&quot; height=&quot;1000&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Momtaj Mansur。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;插图：Matt Rota/The Guardian&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/图>; &lt;p>;在对本文问题的书面答复中，亚马逊承认其沙特工厂的一些工人受到虐待。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“提供安全、健康和公平的工作条件是开展业务的要求亚马逊在我们开展业务的每个国家都与亚马逊合作，我们深感担忧的是，我们在沙特阿拉伯王国的一些合同工……没有得到我们规定的标准待遇，也没有得到他们应有的尊严和尊重。”声明称。 “我们感谢他们愿意挺身而出并报告他们的经历。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;亚马逊表示，它将确保支付招聘费用的工人拿回钱。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span >;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/oct/10/corporate-auditing-foreign-workers-abuse-claims&quot;>;企业正在为工人支付费用内部人士称，滥用审计“旨在失败”&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;该公司补充说，它正在“实施更强有力的控制”，以“确保类似事件不会发生，并提高整体水平”该地区工人的标准”。这包括“为我们的第三方供应商提供有关劳工权利标准的强化培训，特别关注招聘、工资和欺骗”。&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;以有酬就业为幌子的潜在劳动力贩运&lt;/h2>; &lt; p>;本文由美国卫报、国际调查记者联盟 (ICIJ)、NBC 新闻和阿拉伯调查新闻记者制作，作为 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icij.org/investigations/trafficking 的一部分-inc/&quot;>;Trafficking Inc&lt;/a>;，一项联合报告工作，一直在调查&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icij.org/investigations/trafficking-inc/philippine-lenders -and-labor-agents-fleece-workers-seeking-overseas-jobs-interviews-and-confidential-documents-show/&quot;>;亚洲&lt;/a>;，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icij.org/调查/人口贩运公司/性贩运幸存者越来越多地起诉连锁酒店，要求其对其财产的滥用承担责任-新调查发现/&quot;>;美国&lt; /a>;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icij.org/investigations/trafficking-inc/how-torture-deception-and-inaction-underpin-the-uaes-thriving-sex-trafficking-industry/&quot; >;非洲&lt;/a>;和&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icij.org/investigations/trafficking-inc/us-military-bases-trafficked-workers/&quot;>;中东&lt;/a>;。&lt;/在采访中，工人们对亚马逊和劳工中介在其雇佣过程中的不公平做法进行了类似的描述。为了支持他们的账户，他们提供了照片、视频和数百份文件，包括护照、工作合同、机票、抵达文件、亚马逊身份证、工资单、工作许可证、医疗记录和内部聊天消息的屏幕截图。几名前工人公开发言，但现任工人和一些前工人担心遭到报复，要求不公开自己的名字。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些采访描述了根据美国法律和法律被视为潜在劳动力贩运标志的做法。联合国标准，包括使工人处于虐待性的工作和生活条件下，限制他们的行动，并对工资、工作条件和雇主身份做出虚假承诺。联合国标准还规定，私人招聘机构不得向工人收取任何费用或成本；应该由雇主向招聘公司支付费用。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;仓库工人描述的做法似乎也违反了亚马逊的劳工政策。在 2022 年的一份&lt;a href=&quot;https://sustainability.aboutamazon.com/modern-slavery-statement.pdf&quot;>;声明&lt;/a>;中，亚马逊表示其标准“认识到国内外移民工人的独特脆弱性”并且“明确规定，在招聘过程中的任何时候都不得向工人收取招聘费”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;人权组织国际特赦组织向《卫报》和其他媒体合作伙伴证实，它已经对这种待遇进行了自己的调查亚马逊沙特业务的尼泊尔工人。国际特赦组织表示，它与另一个非政府组织合作采访了 22 名工人，他们报告称自己遭受了虐待，包括被迫支付大笔招聘费以及在雇佣条款方面受到欺骗。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;艾拉·奈特 (Ella Knight)，伦敦人国际特赦组织的劳工权利研究员表示，该组织于 6 月份向亚马逊通报了这些问题，并于 8 月份提供了更全面的调查结果细节。奈特表示，国际特赦组织的调查和新闻媒体的单独调查很可能促使亚马逊决定公开承诺实施更强有力的控制，并确保工人得到招聘费用的补偿。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一些尼泊尔人工人们表示，他们不想将所有责任归咎于亚马逊。他们说，如果没有劳动力供应公司阻碍他们在这家跨国公司找到一份真正的工作，他们的处境可能还可以维持下去。一名现任员工表示，他希望公司创始人兼执行董事长杰夫·贝佐斯知道，他在目前的安排下正在遭受痛苦，但他“准备好去亚马逊的任何地方工作，如果是直接招聘的话”。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;世界第三富豪贝索斯誓言要在 2021 年让亚马逊成为“地球上最好的雇主”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一位前员工向贝索斯传达了不同的信息：“你处于这个位置是因为我们的工作。如果没有来自尼泊尔、菲律宾、印度、孟加拉国、巴基斯坦和其他国家的劳工和帮助者的努力，你们就不会处于这样的境地。但你们却忽视了工人的担忧。”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;29bddad04b75576​​6664e04af55f624402569f712&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/29bddad04b75576​​6664e04af55f624402569f712/0_0_5 711_4260/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;一名工人在仓库中搬运箱子的插图&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;746&quot;>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;几位工人表示，亚马逊官员了解他们在沙特面临的许多问题阿拉伯。他们说，工人们向亚马逊仓库经理或人力资源代理抱怨工资低或少、住房条件差以及仓库工作压力大。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“他们了解我们的处境和痛苦，”阿米里·亚达夫 (Amiri Yadav) 说， 2021 年至 2023 年在沙特阿拉伯的亚马逊配送中心工作。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;亚马逊在声明中表示，“我们的供应链审计流程和我们自己的调查发现沙特阿拉伯违反了我们的标准”，这促使其采取行动处理投诉。该公司补充说，“我们工厂的工人可以通过多种方式报告他们所受到的待遇问题，包括 24 小时保密热线。”&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;贫穷的尼泊尔人希望在其中一家工作。全球最大品牌&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;亚马逊于 2017 年大举进军沙特阿拉伯，收购了中东在线零售巨头 Souq.com。后来，该公司将 Souq.com 的沙特业务重新命名为 &lt;a href=&quot;http://amazon.sa/&quot;>;Amazon.sa&lt;/a>;，并通过引进来自巴基斯坦、印度、孟加拉国和尼泊尔的工人来增加劳动力。亚马逊目前在沙特阿拉伯雇佣了近1,500名长期工和季节性工人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;作为亚洲最贫穷的国家之一，尼泊尔长期以来一直是跨国工人的主要来源地。在2010-2011年的人口普查中，超过一半的尼泊尔家庭报告说他们从在国外工作的家庭成员那里收到了钱。 2021年，海外汇款占尼泊尔国内生产总值的近四分之一。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;曼苏尔感到有义务走向海外。他的家人每月靠大约 300 美元的收入以及在他们与叔叔的家人共享的五分之一英亩的土地上种植的稻米、小麦和草豌豆维持生计。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;许多尼泊尔工人都听说过关于出国的家人、邻居工作、生活条件差。他们知道要留意某些国家和雇主，并寻求直接就业，而不是为劳动力供应公司工作。但世界各地的移民和劳工政策往往对他们不利，导致他们最终受到剥削。 2017 年英国著名医学杂志《BMJ》发表的一项调查显示，大多数在国外工作过的尼泊尔男性表示，他们“在移民过程的各个阶段都经历过剥削”。一半的人报告称自己是欺骗性招聘行为的目标。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p>;每个人都被困在国外就业中。不管你有多聪明，最后都会被骗&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;在沙特阿拉伯亚马逊仓库工作的尼泊尔工人&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside >; &lt;p>;“每个人都被困在国外就业”，一名目前在沙特阿拉伯亚马逊仓库工作的尼泊尔工人说道。 “无论你多么聪明，最终都会被欺骗。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些条件迫使农民工做出惨淡的算盘——与其说是寻找最好的着陆点，不如说是寻找最不最糟糕的着陆点。可以赚到足够的工资，让交通和麻烦都值得。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当位于加德满都的尼泊尔招聘公司 Rove International 的代理人告诉他他可以在亚马逊找到一份工作时，曼苏尔做了一些研究。他认为像亚马逊这样的美国大公司可能与许多移民工人遇到的虐待雇主不同。他说，他知道“特工会撒谎”，因此他反复询问自己是否愿意成为亚马逊或劳动力供应公司的员工。曼苏尔说，该代理人“向我证实这是亚马逊的直接雇佣，这将改变我的生活”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当 Rove International 告诉他必须支付招聘费用时，他感到很惊讶费用约为 2,300 美元——特别是因为他知道尼泊尔政府将就业公司向前往沙特阿拉伯的工人收取的费用限制在 85 美元以下。另外六名在亚马逊沙特仓库寻找工作的尼泊尔人证实，Rove International 还向他们每人收取了超过 1000 美元的招聘费。与许多其他尼泊尔工人一样，曼苏尔表示，他支付这笔高昂的费用是因为他不想失去为亚马逊工作的机会。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;罗夫国际公司没有回答本文的详细问题清单。当记者周日参观其位于加德满都的办公室时，一名公司管理人员表示：“我们遵循政府制定的所有法律程序，这些工人知道他们将在哪里以及如何工作。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;尼泊尔工人正在前往据尼泊尔议会、最高法院和美国国务院称，沙特阿拉伯的工人尤其容易受到影响，因为尼泊尔政府未能执行禁止招聘机构收取高额费用的政策。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在一些阿拉伯国家寻找工作的工人由于&lt;em>;卡法拉&lt;/em>;制度，各国也面临风险，该制度是劳动法和移民法的矩阵，使雇主能够“几乎完全控制”移民工人的就业和移民身份，&lt;a href=&quot;https:/ /www.cfr.org/backgrounder/what-kafala-system&quot;>;根据外交关系委员会&lt;/a>;。在沙特阿拉伯和其他仍然存在&lt;em>;卡法拉&lt;/em>;制度形式的国家，许多外国工人担心如果离开雇主，他们会受到惩罚。&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;抵达王国 – 前往令人不快的意外&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;2021 年 9 月，曼苏尔在贷款支付招募费后，从家中前往加德满都，搭乘半岛航空公司的航班——这是他第一次乘坐飞机，第一次离开尼泊尔。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当曼苏尔抵达利雅得时，亚马逊官员会见了曼苏尔和其他尼泊尔工人——至少曼苏尔是这么认为的。他说这些人要求他和其他人签署雇佣合同，但不允许他们阅读文件。曼苏尔说，他们被告知，如果不签字，他们将没有地方睡觉，也没有工作。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;68878906db00da8bf10908b37a1e8a8a74aa40b9&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https: //media.guim.co.uk/68878906db00da8bf10908b37a1e8a8a74aa40b9/0_0_3448_2713/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;插图：亚马逊工人在栅栏后面，保安在一旁观看。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;787&quot;>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;“我没有阅读该文件就签署了文件，因为我很害怕，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;几天后，曼苏尔意识到在机场迎接他的人可能不是亚马逊官员。他开始在利雅得的亚马逊配送中心工作，并注意到他的绿色身份徽章与许多其他工人佩戴的蓝色徽章不同。一位巴基斯坦同事解释说，佩戴蓝色徽章的工人是亚马逊直接雇用的。那些佩戴绿色徽章的人毕竟不是亚马逊员工。他们是临时工。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;事实证明，曼苏尔的实际雇主是 Abdullah Fahad Al-Mutairi Co，这是一家沙特劳动力供应公司，通过向亚马逊和其他大公司出售劳动力来获利。记录显示，尼泊尔外国就业部门于 2021 年 9 月向曼苏尔和其他 36 名尼泊尔人发放了工作许可证，他们的劳动合同由尼泊尔招聘公司 Rove International 转给 Al-Mutairi。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;其中 49 人接受本文采访的 54 名尼泊尔工人表示，他们为 Al-Mutairi 工作。一些人表示，他们在离开尼泊尔之前就意识到了这一点，并继续前行，因为他们已经花了钱来支付招募费。但&lt;strong>; &lt;/strong>;42 人表示，他们直到抵达沙特阿拉伯之后才知道真相，而且在大多数情况下，是在他们贷款支付大笔招聘费用之后才知道真相。他们知道收回这些费用的机会很小，因此他们不得不留在沙特阿拉伯 - 为一个他们不想工作的雇主工作，以偿还贷款，使他们有可能找到不再工作的工作&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;更糟糕的是，工人们说，劳动力供应公司没有提供同工同酬。根据 ICIJ 获得的对工人的采访以及工资单和雇佣合同，在亚马逊仓库做白班的尼泊尔工人的月薪一般约为 350 美元。相比之下，几名尼泊尔工人表示，从事类似工作但属于亚马逊直接员工的同事每月收入约为 800 至 1,300 美元。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“搞什么鬼？”曼苏尔说。 “We worked more and harder, but the salary we received was much less.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Al-Mutairi did not respond to requests for comment.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In its statement, Amazon said that since it learned about the violations of its standards, it has worked closely with the Saudi firm “to align on a compliance plan, which they&#39;ve agreed to, that addresses those violations and complies with our standards. This includes ensuring their employees are repaid for any unpaid wages or worker-paid recruitment fees, are provided clean and safe accommodations, and that the vendor is committed to ensuring ongoing protections for workers.”&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;A dream job becomes a nightmare&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;Amazon&#39;s warehouses in Saudi Arabia are massive. Its newest distribution center, opened in Riyadh in May, spans 390,000 sq feet across five floors, with a capacity of 2.7m cubic feet. It can hold more than 9m items – enough, Amazon says, to fill 30 Olympic-size swimming pools.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Inside Amazon&#39;s distribution centers, the pace is fierce. Pickers roam the floors, grabbing items and handing them off to packers, who stand for hours at a time. Workers say managers keep watch on pickers through closed-circuit cameras and pickers&#39; scanners, which list them as “idle” if they&#39;re not scanning items rapidly enough. Nepali workers report that senior-level Amazon staffers stalk them up and down the aisles of the warehouse, yelling, “&lt;em>;Yalla! Yalla!&lt;/em>;” – an Arabic exclamation meaning “hurry up”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Over a normal shift, Mansur says, he and other pickers covered as many as nine miles across warehouse floors. “I would feel extremely weak. My legs would hurt,” he says. “When I returned home, I would feel like I was being pierced with needles or walking barefoot on stones. My whole body would ache.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;During rush periods – such as sales or holidays – supervisors monitored restroom activity, sometimes admonishing them, workers say, for taking too much time away from the warehouse floor.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“They wanted us not to take breaks when there was a high work demand,” says Surendra Kumar Lama, who worked at an Amazon warehouse in Saudi Arabia from 2021 until the end of 2022. “They would stand near restrooms and water stations because workers are afraid of them. Many times, I waited half an hour or an hour to go to the restroom because they were there.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;After long days at Amazon&#39;s warehouses, workers come home to living accommodations provided by Al-Mutairi. Many say the housing units are cramped and squalid, with cockroaches scuttling across the floor and a limited and salty water supply that led to rashes and hair loss. Often, workers say, six to eight men sleep and eat packed together in one room arrayed with bunk beds.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“How can eight people stay together in a small room?” Mansur says. “There was no space to put personal belongings. We would keep those on our beds.”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;9a3e7558f56450da0255dba20d7eedfd39ec4e77&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/9a3e7558f56450da0255dba20d7eedfd39ec4e77/0_0_5709_4100/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Illustration of a room with multiple bunkbeds and workers relaxing&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;718&quot;>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;In some cases, workers successfully lobbied Amazon officials to prod Al-Mutairi to address the housing problems. But improvements often didn&#39;t last, and the lack of clean water continues to be a problem, workers say. When they reported the water issue to Amazon, says one former worker, “Al-Mutairi threatened us: &#39;Who complained about this? We will make him jobless!&#39;”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The labor supply company also makes things difficult, workers say, when they try to get time off to attend funerals, births and other family events back home in Nepal. In such cases, 23 current and former workers say, Al-Mutairi gives a worker two choices. He can pay a large fine upfront. Or he can persuade co-workers to sign a “guarantor” contract agreeing to pay a fine on his behalf if he doesn&#39;t return to Saudi Arabia to complete his contract.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;One former worker says he missed the birth of his son and his father&#39;s funeral because Al-Mutairi wouldn&#39;t let him go home. Even after he showed the firm his father&#39;s death certificate, he says, the company said he could go only if he paid a $1,600 penalty – more than four months&#39; salary. He couldn&#39;t afford it, and he couldn&#39;t find a co-worker willing to sign as his guarantor, he says.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p>;I couldn&#39;t be with my dad when he died. I couldn&#39;t hold my son when he came into this world. I didn&#39;t achieve anything, but I lost many things&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;Former Amazon worker in Saudi Arabia&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“I couldn&#39;t be with my dad when he died. I couldn&#39;t hold my son when he came into this world,” he says. During his time in Saudi Arabia, “I didn&#39;t achieve anything, but I lost many things.”&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;At the whim of a powerful company&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;One afternoon in May 2022, a few hours before his next shift began, a message popped up on Mansur&#39;s mobile phone: “Don&#39;t go to duty,” it said, and listed dozens of names as “people stopped from Amazon”. He searched and found his own name.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I didn&#39;t know why I was fired. Nobody knew why they were fired,” he says. “I was working well.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The laborers from Nepal had come to the Persian Gulf expecting they would be working difficult but steady jobs. Instead, they found that job security was almost nonexistent. Workers say Amazon lets go of large numbers of temporary workers from its warehouses when customer orders slow – and tracks workers&#39; lapses and uses them as excuses for dismissing individuals. These failings can include not meeting targets for picking items, pulling the wrong products off shelves or using a personal cellphone in the warehouse.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Every day, we fear that we could be terminated the next day. We work every day as the last day of our work,” says a Nepali still working in an Amazon warehouse in Riyadh.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Workers say their sense of fear grew after thefts of iPhones and other items from Amazon&#39;s warehouses prompted the company to tighten security. They claim security guards became more suspicious of Nepali workers and raised false allegations against some of them as a pretext for firing them.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The security guards have so much power that even managers can&#39;t help the workers,” says Hem Thapa, who worked in multiple Amazon warehouses in Saudi Arabia.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sanjay Kumar Mahara, who worked as a picker, says he was falsely accused of stealing earlier this year when he accidentally pulled out two pieces of jewelry from a shelf as he was trying to fill an order for one piece.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A guard stopped him in the aisle, searched the tote bag he used to carry items from the shelves to the packers, found the two items and then took him to a manager, Mahara says. As the guard and manager spoke in Arabic – which Mahara couldn&#39;t understand – Mahara tried to tell his side of the story in English.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He was told not to come back to the warehouse while the problem was being worked out, he says, but after several days Al-Mutairi put him on a flight back to Nepal.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“If any mistakes are made at work, Amazon should investigate and try to solve the issue,” Mahara says. “But they rush to terminate the workers. I feel injustice. But what can I do?”&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;No job, squalid housing, little food&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;Once they&#39;re fired or laid off, workers say, a new ordeal begins. They&#39;re booted out of housing reserved for those working at Amazon, they say, and shunted to even worse housing set aside for those without jobs. They receive no wages or food allowance. Many languish for weeks or months, they say, waiting for Al-Mutairi to place them back with Amazon or some other business.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p>;I cry out when I look back at my past month. I never imagined I could have such a life&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;A recently fired worker stuck in Riyadh&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“I cry out when I look back at my past month,” says a recently fired worker who is stuck in Riyadh. “I never imagined I could have such a life.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Unemployed Nepalis describe their new lodgings as “dirty” and “abandoned” – a building without beds or internet service. When workers get laid off en masse, they often can&#39;t find even a tiny space in the building to sleep because it is already occupied by dozens of other jobless workers.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;During Mansur&#39;s time there, he survived by eating &lt;em>;kuboos –&lt;/em>; Arab flatbread – once a day and borrowing money from his former co-workers. Some days, he says, he didn&#39;t eat at all. When his friends couldn&#39;t support him any more and Al-Mutairi didn&#39;t find him another job, he decided to ask his family to take out a big loan so he could pay the exit penalty and go back to Nepal.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The only way to escape, he says, was to pay the $1,300 fee demanded by the labor supply firm as a penalty for leaving before the end of his two-year contract. It was an enormous sum for Mansur and his family.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the end, his family sunk itself even deeper in debt by taking out a loan – at 36% interest – to pay the exit fee.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It was better going home than dying of hunger,” he says.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Other jobless workers slipped away from the accommodations and worked illegal, off-the-grid jobs.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Loneliness, hunger and stress pushed many jobless workers toward dark turns of thought. Yadav, one of the workers who says he was fired after being falsely accused of theft, says Al-Mutairi managers refused to let him go home to Nepal until he threatened to “record a video complaining about you and commit suicide”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Manish Kumar Sodari, another worker who landed in the oblivion of unemployment, says he spent days caring for another laid-off worker who was talking about hanging himself. Soon, Sodari says, he began having suicidal thoughts himself.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“How can one stay helpless for three to four months?” he told a reporter in January. “I have already suffered a lot. I am at the last stage.”&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;Home – for now&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;Sodari got home by getting himself arrested. He did this, he says, with help from a man who is familiar with how difficult it is for Nepali workers to escape Saudi Arabia. The man advised him to go to a certain street and loiter until he was approached by a police officer.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sodari says he was taken to jail after admitting he didn&#39;t have a job or valid residency permit. He spent about two weeks in detention, he says, then the Saudi government deported him. He stayed briefly in Nepal before heading out to seek a job in India.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Another former Amazon warehouse worker, Thapa, returned to Nepal before taking a job in India at a garment store. He had to leave home again to find work, he says, because almost all of his earnings in Saudi Arabia went to repay the loan that had paid the recruiting fee for his Amazon job.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote>; &lt;p>;I couldn&#39;t save money working in Saudi. I went empty-handed. I returned empty-handed&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;A former Amazon warehouse worker&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“I couldn&#39;t save money working in Saudi,” he says. “I went empty-handed. I returned empty-handed.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Other former Amazon workers are in worse financial shape. They&#39;re deep in debt, they say, because of recruiting fees, low wages, layoffs and exit penalties.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Mansur feels guilty about the loans that he and his family took out to get him to the Persian Gulf and bring him back to Nepal. Interest charges are piling up. He fears the village moneylenders will seize the family&#39;s patch of land.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I lost time and money working at Amazon. I lost everything,” he says. “I lost my body and my strength … My family&#39;s financial situation is devastated now.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But like many migrant workers around the globe, Mansur isn&#39;t going to let a harrowing experience stop him from trying to find an employer that pays a fair wage and treats him decently. He&#39;s begun to look again for an overseas job. He&#39;s open to working most anywhere – except Saudi Arabia.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Contributors: freelance journalist Shyam Karki; Delphine Reuter from the ICIJ; Andy Lehren and Anna Schecter from NBC News; Tanka Dhakal, Eman Alqaisi, Mara Kessler and Hoda Osman from Arab Reporters for Investigative Journalism&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;ul>; &lt;li>; &lt;p>;This story was supported by the &lt;a href=&quot;https://fij.org/&quot;>;Fund for Investigative Journalism&lt;/a>; and the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mcgrawcenter.org/&quot;>;McGraw Center for Business Journalism&lt;/a>; at the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.journalism.cuny.edu/&quot;>;Craig Newmark Graduate School of Journalism&lt;/a>; at the City University of New York&lt;/p>;&lt;/li>; &lt;/ul>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 17:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Global economy proving ‘remarkably resilient’ to recent shocks, says IMF]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/oct/10/global-economy-proving-remarkably-resilient-to-recent-shocks-says-imf]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T08:00:34Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/202a21b2281feb037444716003ad88c2972f638e/0_152_4554_2732/master/4554.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=f1d5c8bfb118da5ba9305df6ae38247b&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Shoppers on a wet Oxford Street in London&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Fears of a worldwide recession triggered by the war in Ukraine and a cost of living crisis will prove unfounded, according to a health check from the International Monetary Fund.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In its &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/apr/11/uk-economy-shrink-imf-euro-area-energy-costs-inflation&quot;>;half-yearly world economic outlook&lt;/a>;, which was produced before the surprise attack on Israel by Hamas, the IMF said growth had shown “remarkable resilience” in the face of a series of adverse shocks in recent years with activity slowing but not stalling.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Releasing its update at its annual meeting in Marrakech, the IMF said it detected little evidence of a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2022/jun/20/would-a-wageprice-spiral-cause-inflation-to-get-out-of-control&quot;>;wage-price spiral&lt;/a>; but warned central banks against cutting interest rates too quickly.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It said several headwinds to growth had subsided since its spring meeting in Washington in April. The World Health Organization no longer considered Covid-19 a global health emergency, supply chains had largely returned to normal, and financial conditions had eased after the US and Swiss authorities acted to contain turbulence in their banking sectors.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The World Economic Outlook (WEO) report said global growth was expected to fall from 3.5% in 2022 to 3% this year and 2.9% in 2024. The 2023 forecast was unchanged from the IMF&#39;s last set of predictions in July, with the 2024 estimate revised down by 0.1 percentage points.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US is expected to grow by 2.1% in 2023 and 1.5% in 2024, up 0.3 and 0.5 percentage points respectively since July, while the eurozone is forecast to grow by 0.7% this year and 1.2% in 2024, down 0.2 and 0.3 points respectively.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The UK, despite having its growth forecast revised up by 0.1 points to 0.5% this year, is expected to be &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/jan/31/britain-only-g7-economy-expected-shrink-2023-imf&quot;>;the second weakest economy&lt;/a>; in the G7 group of major industrial nations after Germany, and to fall to the bottom of the league table in 2024 with growth of 0.6%, down 0.4 points on July.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;However, the 2024 forecast is based on an interest rate forecast that the IMF says is out of date. When the WEO was being prepared last month, the IMF&#39;s assumption was that the Bank of England&#39;s ceiling for borrowing costs would be 6%. After Threadneedle Street&#39;s decision to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/sep/21/bank-of-england-keeps-interest-rates-hold&quot;>;pause raising rates&lt;/a>; at the September meeting of its monetary policy committee, the IMF now believes the peak will be 5.25% or 5.5%.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The decline in UK growth reflected “tighter monetary policies to curb still high inflation and lingering impacts of the terms-of-trade shock from high energy prices”, the IMF said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas, the IMF&#39;s economic counsellor, said: “The global economy continues to recover slowly from the blows of the pandemic, Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine, and the cost of living crisis. In retrospect, the resilience has been remarkable.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“As a result, projections are increasingly consistent with a &#39;soft landing&#39; scenario, bringing inflation down without a major downturn in activity, especially in the US, where the forecast increase in unemployment is very modest, from 3.6 to 3.9% by 2025.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Gourinchas said the slowdown was more pronounced in advanced economies compared with emerging markets, and that the US had “surprised on the upside, with resilient consumption” while the eurozone had been revised downward.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He said that even though recession would be averted, the global economy was limping along rather than sprinting.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He highlighted five key risks to the forecasts, namely a real estate crisis in China, a rise in commodity prices, inflation remaining stubbornly high, a crash in financial markets or high levels of borrowing preventing governments from easing policy in the face of fresh shocks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Gourinchas said labour markets in developed economies remained buoyant, with historically low unemployment rates helping to support activity.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“So far, there is scant evidence of a &#39;wage-price spiral&#39; and real wages remain below pre-pandemic levels,” he added.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The WEO said many countries were near the peak of their interest rate raising cycles and little further tightening of policy was warranted. “However, easing prematurely would squander the gains achieved in the past 18 months,” it said.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 16:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Poland’s polarised election campaign heats up ahead of crucial vote – live]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/oct/10/poland-polarised-election-campaign-crucial-vote-live]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T07:31:54Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/6fea806f8f6ee2ed55826046990193d085b68e8f/0_106_8044_4826/master/8044.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=a59829593c381b0155d10b83fc1f8b20&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;People outside a TV studio watch Donald Tusk, leader of the Civic Platform party, candidate in the upcoming Polish elections, taking part in a debate in Warsaw.&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 15:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Risk of repeat of 1970s-style stagflation, Deutsche Bank warns – business live]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2023/oct/10/stagflation-1970s-fears-deutsche-bank-imf-global-economy-uk-food-inflation-business-live]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T06:42:04Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ebbae42211557b4adc870a80b84a6cab4b18e117/0_185_6000_3600 /master/6000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=1ef45ae02ed1f6b526dcb15597135041&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;伦敦金融城的天际线。&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 14:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia-Ukraine war live: Moscow seeks return to UN human rights council; Russia wants war in Middle East, Zelenskiy says]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/oct/10/russia-ukraine-war-live-un-human-rights-council-putin-zelenskiy-latest-updates]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T06:46:48Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/815995770dbb160f131de332b746c2ff44761a94/0_50_6720_4032 /master/6720.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=ceb5118d974dd055c3c6372eaeca4ea0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;乌克兰陆军无人机部队侦察敌方阵地的成员。 &lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 14:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Uncharted territory’: more than 2m fungi species yet to be discovered, scientists say]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/oct/10/uncharted-territory-kew-scientists-say-more-than-2m-fungi-species-waiting-to-be-identified-aoe]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T06:00:31Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7ba3d6cf87a40871185bdeedb62d5255ff867a5c/0_0_2709_1808 /master/2709.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=96d3a063c2e4e68ef8e88ae544966df1&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;灵芝蘑菇生长在莫桑比克北部马布山森林深处的枯木上，该地区是数十种新物种的家园。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;根据一份新报告，世界各地有超过 200 万种真菌物种正在等待鉴定，科学家们将其称为地球生命的“发现新领域”。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但研究人员也警告说，绝大多数新发现的植物都是濒临灭绝的物种，默认情况下它们应该被列为濒临灭绝的物种，并警告说，四分之三的未描述物种可能面临消失的风险.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;从人类微生物组的居民到地球上已知最大的陆地生物，真菌的多样性仅次于无脊椎动物 - 它们存在于空气中、动植物体内以及自然界中。土壤和海洋，有多种形状和大小。据英国皇家植物园 (Kew) 的研究人员称，其中 90% 以上仍不为科学所知，&lt;a href=&quot;https://nph.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/hub/global-plant-diversity-and-distribution -special-collection&quot;>;谁发布了真菌多样性的新估计&lt;/a>;，作为世界植物和真菌健康报告的一部分，发现可能有大约 250 万种，但迄今为止仅识别出 155,000 个。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这是一个未知的领域，”皇家植物园 (RBG Kew) 科学主任亚历山大·安东内利 (Alexandre Antonelli) 教授说道。 “在过去的几年里，我们越来越认识到真菌在一切事物中的作用……它们维持着我们的生命、我们的植被，它们对每一个动物物种都至关重要。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“现在我们有 DNA 分析，我们正在努力突破前沿。探索外层宇宙与探索外层宇宙非常相似。真菌是暗物质。”&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jan/09/fungi -extreme-heat-aoe&quot;>;关于真菌的紧迫问题：在极端高温下它们会发生什么？&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;科学家们对这个未被发现的世界的兴奋因对真菌的担忧而减弱。许多新发现的物种面临灭绝的威胁。研究人员发现，在 2020 年确定的维管植物物种中，超过 77% 的物种已达到受威胁标准，59% 的物种可能达到濒危标准，24% 的物种可能达到极度濒危标准。 RBG Kew 报告估计，科学界已知的维管植物有 350,000 种，研究人员相信约有 100,000 种尚未被识别，但其中三分之一可能面临灭绝的威胁。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;邱园科学家表示，所有新描述的物种都应被视为受到威胁，除非有其他证据。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;世界各地的研究人员正在鼓励公众帮助他们的鉴定工作，这些工作已被新的 DNA 彻底改变。测序技术在一茶匙土壤中发现了数百种真菌。 &lt;a href=&quot;https://fungiforthefuture.org/&quot;>;在荷兰&lt;/a>;，一项计划为公众提供了命名在送至实验室的土壤样本中发现的任何新真菌物种的机会。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;自 2020 年以来，大约有 10,200 个新真菌物种被正式描述，但科学进步意味着研究人员希望他们每年能够识别 50,000 个新真菌物种。今年，Kew &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/mar/17/parasitic-fungus-that-infects-and-kills-spiders-discovered-in-brazil-aoe&quot;>;研究人员表示，他们在巴西大西洋雨林中发现了一种新的寄生真菌，这种真菌以活板门蜘蛛为食，类似于僵尸蚂蚁真菌，这种真菌&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/ pii/S0166061617300593&quot;>;战胜昆虫&lt;/a>;并诱骗它们离开巢穴前往可以传播孢子的地方。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt; a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/oct/07/kew-gardens-alexandre-antonelli-hidden-universe-book-interview-state-worlds-plants-fungi&quot;>;邱园亚历山大·安东内利（Alexandre Antonelli）：“我们可能在注意到物种之前就已经失去了它们”&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;RBG Kew 的高级研究员埃斯特·加亚（Ester Gaya）专注于真菌，她表示她希望能够识别更多物种物种可能会带来医学、农业和工程方面的进步，并有助于更好地了解人类疾病。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“DNA 技术彻底改变了真菌研究，其程度远远超过植物和动物。最初我们只关注蘑菇和地衣，”她说。 “现在，重点是肠道微生物组。现在，许多人类疾病都被证明是由真菌或真菌群落不平衡引起的。地下真菌将树木连接起来，与树根建立共生关系，交换养分和水分。你现在正在呼吸真菌的孢子。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;报告称，识别和描述新的植物和真菌物种是生物多样性科学面临的一项重大挑战。研究人员强调了 32 个存在严重知识差距的植物多样性“黑点”，其中哥伦比亚、新几内亚和中国中南部的差距最大。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“问题是我们存在很多知识差距。我们在世界上很多地方还没有收集到足够的[植物]，或者收集到的生物多样性比例非常有偏差，”安东内利说。 “[暗点]的想法实际上是为了确定我们可以获得最大成本效益的领域。新科学发现的最大奖励系统。”&lt;/p>; &lt;ul>; &lt;li>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;查找更多&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://front/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/fronts /environment/series/the-age-of-extinction&quot;>;灭绝年龄报道&lt;/a>;，并关注生物多样性记者&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/phoeb0?lang=en&quot;>;Phoebe Weston &lt;/a>; 和 &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/pgreenfielduk?lang=en&quot;>;Patrick Greenfield&lt;/a>; 在 X（以前称为 Twitter）上了解所有最新新闻和功能&lt;/em>; &lt;/p>;&lt;/li>; &lt;/ul>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 14:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Myanmar: at least 30 people killed in attack on camp for displaced people]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/10/myanmar-at-least-30-people-killed-in-attack-on-camp-for-displaced-people]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T06:03:54Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/f419bf6b9acd87037263114916554a4208572ceb/0_96_3000_1801 /master/3000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=15761a8667b9fd829c753000873429d3&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;缅甸克钦邦一个城镇的资料照片。据报道，该州的袭击已造成 30 多人死亡。 &lt;/div>;&lt;p>;据媒体报道和当地活动人士称，缅甸克钦邦一个流离失所者营地遭到袭击，造成至少 30 人死亡，其中包括幼儿。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;数十人死亡。据报道，周一晚上 11 点 30 分左右，袭击发生在缅甸最北端的克钦邦，造成更多人受伤。社交媒体上，未经证实的图像显示，黑暗中，男子从废墟中抬着受害者，其中包括一名小孩。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;拉扎的一位匿名克钦族活动人士告诉《卫报》，有 33 人被杀，其中包括13名儿童。她说，被杀害的儿童中有一名三个月大的婴儿。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/ world/2023/sep/07/myanmar-journalist-jailed-for-20-years-for-cyclone-coverage&quot;>;缅甸记者因报道飓风被判入狱 20 年&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p >;她补充说，死亡人数可能会进一步上升，因为该地区非常大，而且志愿者仍在打捞尸体。她补充说，营地里的房子建在山上，所以房子都被埋在土里了。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“营地里的房子彼此距离很近，所以情况完全混乱， ”她说，并补充说，这次袭击只是军方“不人道行为”中的最新一起。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这样的案例还有很多，这不是唯一的案例，”她说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;p>;袭击发生在 Mong Lai Khet 国内流离失所者营地，距离克钦独立军 (KIA) 管理的军营几公里，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/ jun/04/in-the-targets-of-the-junta-life-and-war-inside-rebel-held-myanmar&quot;>;与 2021 年夺取政权的缅甸军政府作战的众多团体之一&lt;/a>; .&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该地区靠近中国边境，近几个月武装冲突频繁。联合国警告称，克钦邦和该国许多其他地区的人道主义准入受到限制，需求达到了可怕的程度。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;目前尚不清楚周二的袭击是重型火炮还是空袭的结果。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;军队经常&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/31/monster-from-the-sky-two-years-on-from-缅甸军政府政变增加对平民的空袭&quot;>;被指控袭击平民场所&lt;/a>;，包括医院、学校、宗教场所和平民住宅。去年&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/oct/24/myanmar-military-air-strike-kills-dozens-at-concert-says-kachin-separatist-group&quot; >;军方在针对克钦邦一场音乐会的空袭中造成 60 人死亡，其中包括音乐家和儿童。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;无法立即联系到克钦独立军置评。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;克钦和平网络民间社会团体的当地知名活动人士孔嘉 (Khon Ja) 告诉路透社，她曾参观过当地医院。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“袭击发生在午夜。炸弹威力太强……村庄被完全摧毁并消失了，”她说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;袭击发生的同一天，缅甸驻联合国大使 Kyaw Moe Tun 告诉联合国委员会，自政变以来，军方已进口了价值超过 10 亿美元的武器和原材料，实施“焦土政策”，该政策已杀害了 4,000 多名平民，其中包括妇女和儿童，迫使约 200 万人流离失所，摧毁或烧毁了 75,000 多座房屋。 ”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kyaw Moe Tun 仍然忠于文官政府，并不代表军政府，他引用了研究人员的数据，表明从 1 月到 6 月，缅甸平均每月发生 30 次空袭今年，并敦促会员国和安理会对缅甸军队实施全面武器禁运。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“任何言语都无法充分表达缅甸人民所遭受的苦难。这是一场难以形容的悲剧。”Kyaw Moe Tun 说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2022/feb/01/myanmar-coup-a- Year-under-military-rule-in-numbers&quot;>;自 2021 年 2 月夺取政权以来&lt;/a>;，军队一直面临着武装抵抗组织的坚决反对，其中包括政变后形成的武装团体以及规模更大的武装团体。克钦独立军几十年来一直与军队作战，为逃离军事暴行的抗议者、政客和其他人提供庇护，并训练来自反对政变的新团体的战士.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Mong Lai Khet 国内流离失所者营地自 2011 年克钦独立军与军方之间的停火协议破裂以来一直存在。 It has grown in size since the 2021 coup, however, as growing numbers have been displaced.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The conflict has forced 2 million people to flee their homes, an unprecedented number in the country, according to the UN, caused soaring poverty and the collapse of education and health services.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 14:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[China to hold nationwide survey on population changes as birthrate plummets]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/10/china-to-hold-nationwide-survey-on-population-changes-as-birthrate-plummets]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-10-10T04:48:46Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/16ff745127b6b5813ca69fe25eaacd913c306ed8/0_139_4027_2416 /master/4027.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=9a1f14f71d0d4a1412f5769630117922&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;妇女带着孩子在公园散步&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;中国国家统计局将在全国范围内开展调查11 月抽样调查，以帮助更好地规划人口政策，因为当局正在努力推动&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/17/chinas-population-falls-for-first- 60多年#:~:text=中国人口跌至1.412，连续几年增长放缓&amp;amp;text=网上，一些中国人，低出生率依然存在。&quot;>;国家低生育率&lt; /a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;出于对中国六十年来人口首次下降和快速老龄化的担忧，北京正在紧急尝试&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/mar /10/free-college-and-ivf-help-china-hunts-for-ways-to-raise-its-birthrate&quot;>;一系列提高中国出生率的措施&lt;/a>;，包括财政激励措施和加强儿童保育设施。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据官方媒体周二报道，此次人口变化调查范围将重点关注全国城乡地区。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span >;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/beijings-demographic-crisis-means-china-could-get-old-before-it-gets-rich&quot;>;北京人口危机意味着中国可能未富先老&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;《规划》将有助于“准确及时监测我国人口发展变化，为党和政府提供依据”。该局表示，“政府制定国民经济、社会发展和人口相关政策”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国上一次进行十年一次的人口普查是在 2020 年 11 月，结果显示，中国的经济增长速度是自 2020 年 11 月以来最慢的。 20世纪50年代第一次现代人口调查。接受调查的人数没有具体说明。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;调查将于 11 月 1 日开始进行，届时政府调查机构将走访家庭收集数据或要求受访者在线填写问题。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;在出生率下降和公民普遍担心抚养孩子困难的情况下，官方媒体经常将人口发展与国家的实力和“复兴”联系起来。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;高儿童保育率高昂的成本以及不得不停止自己的职业生涯，让许多女性不愿生更多的孩子，甚至根本不想生孩子。性别歧视和对妇女照顾孩子的传统陈规定型观念在全国各地仍然普遍存在。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;近几个月来，当局加大了关于分担抚养孩子责任的言论，但大多数省份的陪产假仍然受到限制。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;中国报告称，2022 年人口为 14.1175 亿，减少约 85 万人，这是自 1961 年（中国大饥荒的最后一年）以来首次下降。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 10 Oct 2023 13:22:01 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>